TY  - JOUR
T1  - R&D/Returns Causality: Absorptive Capacity or Organizational IQ
AU  - Knott, Anne Marie
Y1  - 2008/11/05
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0933
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0933
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2054
EP  - 2067
VL  - 54
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Absorptive capacity is the principle that assimilating new knowledge requires prior knowledge. The attendant prescription is to invest more in R it is that some firms have higher returns to R&D, thus they invest more. I conduct an empirical test of the competing views and find that (1) firms differ in the output elasticities of their own R&D (IQ) as well as the elasticities of spillovers from rivals, (2) absorptive capacity becomes insignificant when accounting for that heterogeneity, (3) R&D investment increases with IQ, but (4) R&D investment has no impact on a firm's ability to benefit from spillovers.
AB  - Absorptive capacity is the principle that assimilating new knowledge requires prior knowledge. The attendant prescription is to invest more in R it is that some firms have higher returns to R&D, thus they invest more. I conduct an empirical test of the competing views and find that (1) firms differ in the output elasticities of their own R&D (IQ) as well as the elasticities of spillovers from rivals, (2) absorptive capacity becomes insignificant when accounting for that heterogeneity, (3) R&D investment increases with IQ, but (4) R&D investment has no impact on a firm's ability to benefit from spillovers.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0933
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.1080.0933
Y2  - 2024/03/28
