TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technical Note—Price Promotions in Asymmetric Duopolies with Heterogeneous Consumers
AU  - Sinitsyn, Maxim
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0931
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1080.0931
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2081
EP  - 2087
VL  - 54
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this note I investigate the outcome of a static price competition between a strong firm (a firm with an established loyal consumer base) and a weak firm (a firm without loyal consumers). The consumers are divided into the strong firm's loyal segment and the switching segment, members of which have heterogeneous tastes for the firms' products. In the presence of loyal consumers, for a large set of the parameters of the demand function, the firms use mixed strategies over a finite number of prices. These strategies can be interpreted as occurrences of sales. The most common case is that of the strong firm's using two prices and the weak firm's using one price. However, when both firms use sales, the weak firm promotes more often than the strong firm.
AB  - In this note I investigate the outcome of a static price competition between a strong firm (a firm with an established loyal consumer base) and a weak firm (a firm without loyal consumers). The consumers are divided into the strong firm's loyal segment and the switching segment, members of which have heterogeneous tastes for the firms' products. In the presence of loyal consumers, for a large set of the parameters of the demand function, the firms use mixed strategies over a finite number of prices. These strategies can be interpreted as occurrences of sales. The most common case is that of the strong firm's using two prices and the weak firm's using one price. However, when both firms use sales, the weak firm promotes more often than the strong firm.
